{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_elwha_ver01/data/sn88085421/00237282991/1908012001/0209.xml":{"full_text":"MONDAY, JANUARY 20, 1908.\nCASH IS WANTED\nSAVINGS that mean much to shrewd patrons. The foremost of January's Home\nFurnishing sale Events-Continuing preeminentjin its offering of convincing Clearance\nValues-Complete stock and in such splendid variety as enables everyone to par\nticipate--Stronger inducements were never held forth to prospective buyers.\nOur furniture stock has been the pride of this establishment, but pride has\nno place alongside of necessity, so prices are slashed to the very depth of possibility\nIf You Need An Iron Bed Read This Over\nTHE FOLLOWING ARE FOUR OF OUR IRON BED SPECIALS WHICH W T ILL MERIT YOUR INSPEC\nTION. COME IN AND LOOK OVER THE ENTIRE LINE.\nA highly artistic designed bed; ten con- A strong designed bed in dark green;\ntinuous fillers connected to top rail with 1 n^nuous ft Hers with ornamented chills;\nfancy chilled design; heavy corner chills. m fancy shaped corner chills; swell designed\nRegular price $9.50; January sale price... I\u25a0\u25a0 I top. Regular price $11.00; January sale\n$6.69\n1I I I I I 9- SBBaaSSlihil price $7.29\nA simple and plain straight lined bed; L jUg p A continuous tubing bed with oval top\nrxtra strong pillars ten full length fillers, U Wffi, jjfj flsj design: sixteen full length fillers; double\nheavy corner chills with brass top vases. top rail; a very strong and durable bed.\nRegular price $8.00; January sale price Regular price $8.50: January sale price\nRug Snaps\nRug buyers will surely be\ninterested in the following, as\nthey are exceptionally good\nfigures:\n9xl2ft. Tapestry Brussels Rugs:\nyix patterns to select from (10\nwire): suitable for living room,\ndining room or parlor. Regular\nprice $21.50; sale $14.95\nNavajo Indian Rugs, size 3x5 and\n3x6 feet. These rugs are made\nfrom the ffnest select Arizona\nwool; the colors are dyed with\nthe best vegetable Indian dyes\nand are guaranteed not to fade.\nRegular $7.95 and $6.95: sale\n$3.95 and $2.95\nDomestic Oriental Rugs. These\nare made by patented proc\ncess; look like the genuine Ori\nentals; knotted, fringed and\nindestructible. Regular $5.50;\nsal.- $3.79\n8 ft. 3 in. x 11 ft. 6 in. Mohair\nRugs, made in France; quite\nlike the genuine in weave and\ndesign. We have a limited\nquantity of them and to close\nare offering exceptionally low.\nRegular fSd.VM);' sale $29.95\nMorris Chairs Re\nduced\nNo. 348, worth $8.00. special $4.97\nNo. 354, worth $11.50, special $7;43\nNo. 935, worth $24.00, special $19.50\nNo. 248. worth $19.00, special $14.85\nNo. 510, worth $22.00. special $16.68\nNo. 355. worth $14.00. special $11-80\nNo. 334, worth $21.75, special $15.90\nAll 25c Popular\nSheet Music 19c\n\"Cheynne,\" \"Can You Keep a Sec\nt,\" She Was a Grand Old Lady.\n\"Fun Bob.\" -Tickled to Death.\"' \"Jack\nFrost,'' \"Yesterday,\" \"Idaho,\" and\nmany others.\nTHE DAVIS-KASER CO.\nDon't You Want a Buffet?\nHere is the opportunity. Watch our window\ndisplay. For just three days these tremenduous cuts\n\u2014Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday\u2014on Buffets,\nRemember just three days on these Buffets.\nNo. 551 Golden Oak Buffet, worth $29.50; Special ....$19.88\nThis is a decidedly novel designed Buffet, and sure W>\nplease the most exacting critic. Plain top panel with\nmirror and shelf; large grain and highly polished top;\nt,wo small drawers, one felt lined: one commodious cabi\nnet with a beautiful designed leaded glass door; French\nlegs, shaped feet, cast brass trimmings $19.88\nNo. 100\u2014Golden Oak Buffet, worth $26.50; Special $17.38\nThis Buffet is very plain in design and perfect in con\nstruction; neatly designed top panel, with mirror; two\nsmall and one full length linen drawer: one center 2-door\nleaded glass cabinet: plain cast brass trimmings; made\nof select quarter-sawed oak; highly finished. January\nPrice $17.38\nNo. 908\u2014Golden Oak Buffet, worth $38.50; Special $27.19\nThis is an attractive design, with full shaped front and\nhand-carved claw feet: beautiful top panel with full\nwidth mirror and fancy and artistic designed side draw\ners; two small lined drawers, one full width center\ncabinet and one lower full width drawer: shaped legs;\nbeautifully grained and finished- January Price $27.19\nNo. 817\u2014Golden Oak Buffet, worth $40.00; Special $29.96\nThis is a handsome designed Buffet: fancy shaped top\npanel with triple plate mirrors and side brackets; base\ncontains three top small drawers, lined; one large two\ndoor leaded glass cabinet; one lawer full length linen\ndrawer; shaped legs and claw feet. January Price $29.96\nNo. 20\u2014Weathered Oak Buffet, worth $49.00; Special $32.73\nThis is a perfect type of Mission furnituer: massive top\npanel plate rack and full width French bevel plate mir\nror; base has two small center drawers, and one\ncenter leaded glass door cabinet; two side one-door\ncabinets and one lower full length linen drawer, solid\ncopper trimmings. Price now $32.73\nNo. 818\u2014Weathered Oak Buffet, worth $32.50; Special ....$21.37\nThis Buffet is a most attractive and elegant design of the\nMission style; large full width top mirror: base has one\nlarge three-shelf .cabinet in centre with open side\nshelves; heavy posts; massive copper trimmings. Janu\nary Price 2l 37\nt\nNo 187\u2014Golden Oak Buffet, worth $60.00; Special $38.19\nmost clcverlv designed Buffet: the top has a triple\nplate mirror; a massive shelf with two small drawers\nand two side one-door lift pockets: base contains one\nsmall drawer lined, a larger drawer, one full width linen\ndrawer and two side leaded glass door cabinets; shaped\nlegs and massive claw feet: cast brass trimmings. Janu\nary Price 38 1 9\nCOMPLETE HOME FURNISHERS\nTHE EVENING STATESMAN, WALLA WALLA, WASHINGTON.\nA Few bargains\nfrom the China\nDepartment\nIt will more than pay you to\nspend a few hours in this de\npartment, as there are hun\ndreds and hundreds of dandy\nbargains in china and glass\nwave:\n25c Box Writing Paper 19c\n15c Box Writing Paper 12c\n5c Ink Tablet 3c\n85c Glass Stand Lamp with No. 2\nburner and chimney 68c\n50 cent Metal Nickel Plated Hand\nLamp 38c\n25c Best Crockery Mender 19c\n10c Milk Pans 7c\n20c Cake Pans 16c\n$1.00 large Glass Pitcher, now 80c\n25c Glass Syrup Pitchers 19c\n20c Glass Mustard Cups\n10c Table Mats, \"straw\" 7c\n$2.25 Wine Sets, glass, tray, as\nsorted colors, now $1.69 Set\n$2.50 Lemon and Water Sets,\nglass, assorted decorations, now $1.90\n$1.25 China Cracker Jar. bright\nrose decoration, gold trimming.\nnow 94 c\nLot China Sugar and Cream.\nTable full. Regular $2.00, $2.50.\n$3.00, $4.00 and $5.00; now just\nHalf Price\nHardware Bargains\n$20.00 Wilson Wood Heater, this\nmonth only 12.94\nXo. 8 Washington Coal Cook\nStove* this month is being sold\nf \u00b0r $9.88\n$30 Princess Range\u2014you should\nsee this range. Now $22.98\nNorwood Sewing Machine. Cheap\nbut good. January price ....$11.75\nXo. 40S Granite Muffin Pans;\nregular 40c; now 29c\nConvex Sauce Pots; regular\nthis month 44 c\nNo. 120 Perfection Oil Heaters;\nregular $4.00; now $3.56\nPOLITICAL GOSSIP\n(Continued from Page Four.)\nAVashington is generally accepted as\nstrongly republican. Unless the large\nindependent vote is switched away\nfrom the republican nominees and un\nless the large influx of population in\ntne past four years, votes differently,\nit js practically a cinch that a nomina\ntion on the republican tk'ket will be\nequivalent to election. So the big fight\nwill come before the primaries.\nAs a general thing Mead has the best\nof the contest. While he has consistent\nly played the game of the people as\nagainst the politicians, a direct primary\nis his hope, for the \"machine\" would\nkill him under the convention plan. He\nhas the*prestige of the position and the\nbenefit of being known to voters better\nthan other candidates (a benefit he\nlong ago realized and has persistently\ncultivated by tours of the state). By hi?\nappointments he has made enemies of\nthose who did not get places and of\ntheir friends. Although Mead has kept\nevery agreement with the Ankeny\nforces every paper supporting Ankeny\nis fighting Mead, and this probably\nwill force a combine of the Mead and\nJones forces.\nWhat Militates. Against Mead.\nThe Ballinger candidacy is a hard\nblow to Mead, as it means that inter\nests Mead had counted on are not to be\nwith him. The worst thing Mead is up\nagainst, however, is the second choice\nprovision of the primary law. To get\nthe nomination. Mead must have more\nthan 40 per cent of the party vote.\nWith half a dozen active candidates\nand probably a score or more of fav\nored sons in the race in different sec\ntions, the first choice vote will natural\nly be badly split u.o. Ordinarily a voter\nwho will not cast his first choice vote\nfor the incumpent as second choice.\nCosgrove from the first of his cam\npaign has been counting on this.\nThroughout his canvass of the state\nCosgrove has many friends who will\nfive him their first choice ballot and\nthere are others scattered over the\nstate. Under the law if no man gets 40\nper cent of the total vote as first\nchoice the first and second choice votes\nare added for each candidate and the\nhigh man gets the nomination. Cos\ngrove thus has a better chance than\never before to land the prize he has\nsought for years. Yet Mead at the pres\nent writing seems to have the nomin\nation pretty well assured.\nCITY NEWS IN BRIEF\nS. Underwood of Freewater, is re\nceiving surgical treatment at the Wal\nla Walla hospital this week.\nc\nThe home of J. W. Cookerly, South\nFMrst street, was sold Saturday, to\nMrs. Sarah J. Xoblo, the consideration\nbeing $3500. The deal was made\nthrough the firm of Frankland\nBrown.\nUnder the .direction of Prof. A. C.\nJackson, the choir of Saint Paul's Epis\ncopal jhurcn will give a silver recital\nin the church auditorium tomorrow\nevening. A number of the city's best\nsoloists will appear on the program.\n\nPupils of Professor Archibald C\nJackson, of Whitman conservatory of\nmusic, will give a public recital in\nMemorial hall Wednesday evening at S\no'clock. THis will b.' the Hist recital of\nthe season by Prof. Jackson's pupils,\nand an unusually interesting program\nhas bc-en prvpa^ed.\n\nCarl Rop, of the Union, left Saturdaj\nevening lor a four days' visit in Victo\nria, as a guest of the opening of the\nnew Empress hotel there. Many news\npaper men of the state of Washington\nreceived invitations to attend the open\ning of the new hostelry, which repre\nsents an expenditure of approximate\nly, $750,000.\n\nMrs. Anna M. Burford, wife of A. T.\nBurford. died at Saint Mary's hospital\nSaturday afternoon, at 3 o'clock, after\na short illness. The funeral will be held\nfrom the Cookerly undertaking chapel\ntomorrow morning at 10 o'clock. Rev.\nS. G. Fisher, of tfie Central Christian\nchurch, officiating. Interment will be\nin the city cemetery.\n\nS. S. Wills, one cf the well known\npioneers of the Walla Walla valley,\ndied at the home of his son. 628 New\nel street, at 4 o'clock this morning\nafter a brief illness. Death was caused\nby senile decay. Funeral arrange\nments will not be announced until the\narrival of a sister of Mr. Wills from\nMontana.\n\nComplaint in the name of C. L. Win\ngard vs. Walla Walla county, in which\nplaintiff asks for $400 damages for\nthe opening of a road in the southern\nsuburbs of the city, was filed with the\nclerk of the superior court this morn\ning. The answer of the county was filed\nin November, 1903, an I the cas, h;.f\nbeen delayed since (bait time.\n\nTestimony i n the case ->f h. C.\nAdams vs. the Columbia Cft&aJ t ym\npany is all in, but a decision has not\nbeen rendered, as the court asked for\nwritten, rather than oral, arguments.\nThe cas.- was finished Saturday afler\nnoon. Mr. Adam* asks for damages in\nthe sum of $2000 for adeged injury to\nhis land caused by an overflow from a\nditch of the canal company.\n\nScott Z. Henderson. editor of the\nKennewick Reporter, spent yesterday\nin the city looking alter business in\nterests, and visiting with his many\nfriends lure. Mr. Henderson an\nnounced t hat the first issue of the new\npaper will be printed this week, anj\nhe said that the business outlook in\n\"the little city was exceedingly flatter\ning. Ira H. Hamlin, formerly a member\nof the Statesman stalT, is associated\nwith Mr. Henderson in the publication\nof the new paper.\nPERSONAL MENTION\n\nJohn White, of Dixie, is in the city\non business today.\nClyde Freeman has gone to Hot\nLake, Ore., for a short visit.\nC. F. Weiss is in the city from\nMilton today on a brief business visit.\nL E. Scott has gone to Calhoun,\nIdaho, for a visit with friends and\nrelatives.\nHon. E. R. Henderson, of Waitsburg.\nwas a visitor with Garden City friend\"*\nyesterday.\nAnnual\nFraternal Carnival:\n\n5 Under Auspices of\n\niknights on\nI MACCABEES\nAT ARMORY HALL\nj SEVEN DAYS OF I\nELN AND FROLIC I\nCOMMENCING\nI JAN. 27--ENDW6 FEB. 2:\n\nNew Electrical Effects\u2014Finest Entertainment\u2014 T\nUnique Specialties\u2014High Class Vaudeville Artists\nGRAND MIDWINTER EVENT f\n\nCoronation of the Queen, elected by the People Night\n4> of Monday, January 27\u2014Don't Miss It\u2014Admission 15c\n\nAsK For B. <\u00a3l A. Rye\nF OR SALE AT ALL FIRST CLASS BARS\nTlxo Idle Hour\nROSE and FOURTH\n.A. Resort\nFINE WINES. WHISKIES and CIGARS\nT. D. Barclay, ami Mark R. avis'. \u00ab>f\nPrescott,* visited ove\u00bb Sjad\u00aby wim\nfriends In this tity. i\nH. C. Stone anil E. J. are.\ni mong the visitors fr\u00bbtn \u00ab\u00bbnr in\n:he city today. W\nPatrolman Thomas J. Doyle, is! on\nthe sick lb\u00bbt this week with an |at\ntack of the. grippe. 'ij\nH. E. Barr and R. Fi. Mavwe'.tf cf\nDayton, were among visitors* >Vno\nspent Sunday in this city.\nH;Mry Gilbert :;as g.ino to Bujfelue\nvv-t re he will sjm d several iliivs\nio. king utter business interests.\nCounty Treasurer W. J. Honeycutt\nwent to Waitsburg this morning dn\nbrief business and pseasure visit.' 1\nMiss Nona Ri< hurdson, instructor\nthe Yeend school at Valk-y Grove, is\nsuffering this week with an attach of\nthe grip. t .It\nPresident F. W. Kaser. of the Com\nmtrcial club, returned this morning\nfrom Spokane., where he had been for\nseveral days attending the meeting of\nthe Washington State Hardware asso\nciation. 1 J*:|\nMiss Hazel 'Coleman, who 'has bern,\nsuffering with an attack of th* gripp**\nhas recovered and is again attending\nto her studies at Whitman Conserva\ntory of Music.\nH. I. Slures of the Skiles Dry Go\u00bbd*\ncompany, has returned from Spokane,\nv/here he bad been fdr a wwl< trans\nacting business in the interests of\nhis store.\nCapt. lf.| H. Hanger of Dayion.\nwho bad been visiting with his son,\nT. If. Hanger. 434 \u00ab>escent street,\nfor the past week, has returned to hi*, i\nProfessor W. D. Lyman, of \"Whitman\ncollege, returned yesterday from S?w\u00bb-\nkane. where he had been to act as or>\nof the judges in the Spokane-We\nnatehee debate.\nPAGE FIVE.","height":"28536","width":"22062"}}
